      mood: "angry",
      story_type: "folk_tale",
      text: "[GENTLE] Riley’s fingers clenched around the crumpled edges of their star map. [DRAMATIC] The [EMPHASIS]perfect[/EMPHASIS] constellations were ruined—smeared, torn, just like that. [EXCITED] 'It wasn’t FAIR!' they shouted, voice echoing into the quiet night.\n\n[ADVENTUROUS] Without thinking, Riley stomped toward the backyard, boots kicking up dust. The grass prickled against their ankles, but they didn’t care. [DRAMATIC] They needed to [EMPHASIS]move[/EMPHASIS], to [EMPHASIS]feel[/EMPHASIS] something besides the hot, tight feeling in their chest. [WHISPERING] So they ran—past the fence, past the old oak tree, until the world blurred into streaks of silver and black.\n\n[CURIOUS] Then, Riley stopped. [DRAMATIC_PAUSE] The sky above them was alive. Not just stars—whole rivers of light, swirling like paint in water. A comet streaked past, its tail brushing Riley’s cheek like a cool, glowing finger. [GENTLE] They didn’t want it to be beautiful. Not now. But it was.\n\n[JOYFUL] Riley reached out, letting the stardust cling to their skin. It tingled, warm and soft, like holding sunlight. [laugh] The anger still hummed inside them, but quieter now, like a storm that had spent itself. [SLEEPY] The stars pulsed gently, as if whispering, *It’s okay to be tired.* And Riley was. So, so tired.",
